#   SUBS-004: bare `be put` with only the sub dirty exits 206/PUTNONE

**MEDIUM.**  When only a mounted submodule is dirty (parent clean), bare
`be put` correctly recurses and stages the sub blob, but the aggregate command
exits **206/PUTNONE** because the parent sniff's `PUTNONE` ("no changes")
propagates as the command exit.  The relay (`BEActSubsRelay`) runs AFTER the
parent's put action in `BE_PLAN_PUT` and its `-q` only swallows the SUB's NONE,
not the parent's.  DELETE has no such asymmetry — a parent-only bare delete is
a lenient exit-0 no-op, so a sub-only delete returns 0 (see SUBS-005 contrast).

##  Repro
 1. `be get <parent>?master`.
 2. Edit only `vendor/sub/core.c` (leave parent files clean).
 3. `be put`.
 4. stdout lists `put vendor/sub/core.c` and the sub's wtlog gains a real
    `put core.c` row (sub blob IS staged) — but exit is 206/PUTNONE.

##  Expected
Exit 0.  The sub blob was staged, so the bare put did real work; spec: "A clean
sub returns `*NONE`; recursion passes `-q` and treats it as a no-op, so it
never fails a bare `be put`/`delete`."  Symmetrically, a *dirty* sub under a
*clean* parent should make the aggregate succeed.

##  Actual
Exit 206/PUTNONE; the parent's empty-stage `PUTNONE` masks the successful sub
stage.  (Both-dirty works: exit 0 with both blobs staged — confirming the bug
is purely the parent-empty + sub-nonempty combination.)

##  Fix sketch
Make the aggregate exit OK when any sub relay staged work, even if the parent
side is `PUTNONE` — mirror DELETE's lenient parent-empty handling, or have the
top-level `becli` NONE-swallow apply when a sub did real work.  Care: a truly
empty bare put (parent clean AND all subs clean) must still surface PUTNONE.

##  Tests
`test/put/09-sub-only-dirty-exit` (`WILL_FAIL` until fixed);
`test/put/08-sub-stage-all-both-dirty` (passing control).

